{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17620486","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17620486"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:43:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:43:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16627"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16627","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16627"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.59,0,0.35,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9318"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68842"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9318","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9318"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16627"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54299"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5308"},{"type":"tags","id":"8503"},{"type":"tags","id":"10146"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22091"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22391"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23084"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68842","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/68842"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to her general practitioner requesting long-term contraception. She has two children and does not want any more pregnancies for several years. After discussion, she decides to proceed with a progesterone-releasing intrauterine device. She is interested to know how these devices work.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes their primary mechanism of action?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Directly destroys sperm cells in the uterus","Thickens cervical mucus preventing sperm penetration","Prevents implantation through uterine contractions","Prevents ovulation by suppressing follicle development","Causes tubal inflammation blocking fertilisation"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary mechanism of action of progesterone-releasing intrauterine devices is \u003Cstrong\u003Ethickening of cervical mucus which prevents sperm penetration\u003C/strong\u003E. The local release of progesterone also causes endometrial atrophy, making the uterine environment unsuitable for implantation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirectly destroys sperm cells in the uterus\u003C/strong\u003E: progesterone does not have direct spermicidal effects. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrevents implantation through uterine contractions\u003C/strong\u003E: copper intrauterine devices may increase uterine contractility; however, this is not a significant mechanism for progesterone devices.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrevents ovulation by suppressing follicle development\u003C/strong\u003E: while systemic hormonal contraceptives work this way, progesterone intrauterine devices act primarily locally and do not consistently suppress ovulation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECauses tubal inflammation blocking fertilisation\u003C/strong\u003E: progesterone intrauterine devices do not cause significant inflammation of the fallopian tubes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe local delivery of progesterone means that systemic effects are minimal compared to other hormonal contraceptive methods. The devices provide effective contraception for 3-5 years depending on the specific product used.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Progesterone-releasing intrauterine devices work primarily by thickening cervical mucus to prevent sperm penetration.","Local progesterone release causes endometrial atrophy which creates an unsuitable environment for implantation.","Progesterone intrauterine devices provide effective contraception for 3-5 years depending on the specific device."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54299"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16627"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54299","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/54299"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-10T16:16:15+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-10T16:17:09+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9318"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68842"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":